# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Units
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

oakcurric:unit-3452
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How effective is the UN and SDGs on promoting sustainability?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils consider what role international organisations play in sustainability and climate justice."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Understanding the effectiveness of the UN on climate change builds on pupils' knowledge of the UK and the wider world. This unit assesses international efforts to combat climate change. By learning these concepts now, pupils can critically evaluate the UN's role and efficacy. This supports pupils to develop informed and researched opinions toward sustainability.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know how the UK engages with global organisations and its role in international cooperation.
Pupils understand the impact of political decision-making on global and national issues.
Pupils can explain how citizens and governments influence change at local, national, and international levels.""" ;
  curric:id "3452"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.355821Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-uk-and-the-wider-world .

oakcurric:unit-3448
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How does identity affect rights?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces pupils to the concept of multiply identities, pupils consider what impact different identities can have on rights."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Understanding how identity affects rights builds on pupils' awareness of diversity and equality. This unit is timely as it asks pupils to critically think about the intersection of various identities with legal rights. By learning these concepts now, pupils can better advocate for themselves and others.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have explored what personal and national identity means.
Pupils have They have examined rights and responsibilities, including how the law protects against discrimination.
Pupils have considered migration, diversity, and equality, and how people are treated in UK society.""" ;
  curric:id "3448"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.356340Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-identities-and-communities .

oakcurric:unit-3464
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How can we make a difference in society? Active citizenship project"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils are introduced to what an active citizenship project is, how it should be structured and the skills they need to complete one."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Building on their learning of how they can make a positive difference in their communities this unit continues to develop pupils’ knowledge of social issues and the role citizens and organisations have in creating positive change. This knowledge helps pupils to understand how citizens can work together to improve communities and wider society and how they can make their voice heard by those in positions of power.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils understand there are different ways citizens can make a positive difference in their communities
Pupils can explain how young people can take part in democracy and influence decisions.
Pupils can identify opportunities to get involved and work with others to create change.""" ;
  curric:id "3464"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.357388Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-active-citizenship-making-a-positive-difference .

oakcurric:unit-3472
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "What is the nature of the British Constitution?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils consider why we need a separation of powers and whether the current political structures are fit for purpose."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Building on earlier units on democracy and the UK political system, this unit further explores the nature of the British constitution. The unit provides critical insights into how the UK political system operates encouraging students to think critically about the pros and cons of the current system. Understanding the nature of the British constitution is essential learning for informed civic participation.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils understand the key features of the UK democratic system and how it operates.
Pupils explain the roles of government, Parliament, and local authorities.
Pupils can evaluate the strengths and weaknesses of the UK democratic system.""" ;
  curric:id "3472"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.361543Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-politics-parliament-and-government .

oakcurric:unit-3476
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Practising what we have learnt"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils revisit a number of the key concepts covered in earlier units in preparation for their GCSE papers."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit brings together learning from across the entire sequence. It prepares students for answering questions in their GCSE by revisiting the key learning from each thread.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have covered key concepts from across the GCSE Citizenship course, including rights, democracy, power, identity, justice, and the UK’s global role.
Pupils have developed knowledge and understanding of how these concepts interconnect.""" ;
  curric:id "3476"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.362562Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 .

oakcurric:unit-3455
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How are community identities changing?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils explore the concepts of identity, community, migration and belonging."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Building on their learning from key stage 3 pupils explore what makes a community and how the nature of communities can change over time.  Understanding the complexity of identities and communities is crucial for their awareness of diversity and their sense of belonging. This learning helps pupils to reflect on their own identities, understanding others and contribute positively in their communities.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have a general understanding of personal and group identity.
Pupils are familiar with key features of a community, such as shared values, interests, and social roles.
Pupils have an awareness of belonging and how different identities coexist.
Pupils have a basic understanding of why people migrate (e.g. jobs, safety, family) and global connections.""" ;
  curric:id "3455"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.363688Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-identities-and-communities .

oakcurric:unit-3444
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How can we play a part in the legal system?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils consider a range of roles within the legal system, explore what rights citizens have within the justice system and what influence they can have on the law."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Learning how they can play a part in the legal system builds on pupils' knowledge of law and governance. This unit is timely as it highlights opportunities for active participation, such as jury duty, volunteering, or legal advocacy. This knowledge helps pupils understand the role of citizens in the justice system, preparing them for active and engaged citizenship.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils understand basic legal rights and the structure of the justice system.
Pupils know how laws are made and the importance of citizen involvement.
Pupils have have explored key roles in law and government.""" ;
  curric:id "3444"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.367639Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-rights-justice-and-the-law .

oakcurric:unit-3442
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Synopticity: How do different ideas and concepts in Citizenship interconnect?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils revisit key citizenship concepts from previous units and consider how they relate to each other, demonstrating their ability to draw together different areas of knowledge, skills and understanding."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit brings together learning from across the entire sequence. It prepares students for answering extended response questions in their GCSE which will relate to two of more specification themes.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have studied a broad range of citizenship topics including active citizenship, human rights, politics/parliament/government, law, media, economy, and international relations.
Pupils are prepared to integrate knowledge and skills from across the curriculum to deepen their understanding of citizenship.""" ;
  curric:id "3442"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.368700Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 .

oakcurric:unit-3466
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "What are the strengths and weaknesses of the legal system?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils learn how laws are made and enforced and about the purpose and types of punishment."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils foundational understanding of law and its role in society. Pupils examine the strengths and weaknesses of the legal system critically evaluating how laws are applied and enforced in the UK. This knowledge helps them recognise the distinct roles and responsibilities within the legal system, fostering informed and active citizenship as they deepen their level of engagment with politcal and social ideas affecting society.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils can explain what crime is and some causes of criminal behaviour.
Pupils can explain what laws are.
Pupils have a basic understanding of how laws are made.
Pupils have explored the purpose of the justice system.""" ;
  curric:id "3466"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.369241Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-rights-justice-and-the-law .

oakcurric:unit-3458
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How can I be a changemaker in my community?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit enables students to build knowledge and understanding of communities and develop active citizenship skills to make a positive change."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Learning how to be a changemaker in their local community builds on pupils' knowledge of active citizenship. This unit  provides practical tools and strategies for community engagement and advocacy. By exploring these concepts now, pupils are empowered to take initiative and drive positive change in their communities, preparing them to be active and engaged citizens.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have explored the meaning of active citizenship and ways to make a difference in their communities.
Pupils understand identities, rights, and responsibilities in society.
Pupils have explored community issues and explored local issues and the ways people can participate to make a positive difference.""" ;
  curric:id "3458"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.370851Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-active-citizenship-making-a-positive-difference .

oakcurric:unit-3446
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How well has the UK adjusted to its changing relationship with the EU?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils analyse the reasons behind the Brexit referendum and consider what the implications of it have been."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Understanding how the UK has adjusted to its changing relationship with the EU builds on pupils' knowledge of the UK and the wider world. This unit is timely as it explores the political, economic, and social adjustments post-Brexit. By learning these concepts now, pupils can critically evaluate the impacts and ongoing challenges""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know the role of citizens in democracy and understand how they can participate through mechanisms like referendums.
Pupils understand the UK's role in international organisations and their potential influence on global issues.""" ;
  curric:id "3446"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.371369Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-uk-and-the-wider-world .

oakcurric:unit-3456
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "What tools can we use to challenge injustice in our communities?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils consider a diverse range of case studies to develop their understanding of how and why people challenge injustice in their communities."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils growing awareness of social issues and their potential roles as active citizens in addressing them. Understanding the tools to challenge injustice in our communities builds on their existing knowledge of civic responsibility and rights. This unit equips pupils with practical strategies and skills for active citizenship.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know that citizens can take action to bring about change in society.
Pupils know what a community is and how people and organisations work to support it.
Pupils know they have rights and responsibilities as part of a democratic society.
Pupils know that they can play a role in creating a fairer and more inclusive community.""" ;
  curric:id "3456"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.371882Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-rights-justice-and-the-law .

oakcurric:unit-3474
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How do others govern?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment "Pupils compare different types of government from the UK to US and North Korea."@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Understanding how others govern builds on pupils' existing knowledge of the UK political system. This unit broadens pupils comparative understanding of different governmental structures and practices worldwide. By exploring these concepts now, pupils can critically assess the effectiveness of various governance models and examine the diversity of political systems and the impact this has.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils should understand key features of democratic government and how it operates in the UK.
Pupils should be familiar with the structure and roles of UK Parliament and government.
Pupils should know how elections work in the UK and their importance.
Pupils should have a basic grasp of political leadership roles, such as the Prime Minister.""" ;
  curric:id "3474"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.374638Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-politics-parliament-and-government .

oakcurric:unit-3470
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How does the UK play a role in the international community?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils consider the role the UK plays in Europe and the wider world, exploring organisations such as the United Nations and WTO and examining what role the UK has in global problems."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Understanding how the UK plays a role in the international community builds on pupils' knowledge of politics and global issues. This unit is timely as it explores the UK's contributions to international organizations, diplomacy, and global challenges. By learning these concepts now, pupils can better understand the UK's global impact and their role as global citizens.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils understand the UK’s political system and governance.
Pupils have considered global issues.
Pupils can see their role as active global citizens who can engage with international issues.""" ;
  curric:id "3470"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.380103Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 .

oakcurric:unit-3471
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How is UK society diverse and changing?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils explore what identity is and how the UK population is changing considering how diverse the UK is and exploring mutual respect and understanding between different groups within society."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Building on prior learning around identities and communities this unit analyses what identity is, how it can evolve over time and the impact this has on the population and communities in the UK. Through exploring these concepts now pupils can better understand and engage with a range of diverse communities, preparing them to be informed and active citizens.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know what identity means and how individual and group identities are shaped.
Pupils have examined the role of communities in shaping identity and the importance of mutual respect, inclusion, and shared values.
Pupils have considered how social change and migration contribute to the diversity of UK society and how communities respond to change.
Pupils have developed an understanding of the challenges and opportunities that come with living in a diverse society.""" ;
  curric:id "3471"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.386824Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-identities-and-communities .

oakcurric:unit-3475
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Where does power reside in the UK?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils look at the role of local and national government and identify reserved and devolved powers in the UK."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils explore the distribution of power within their country. Understanding where power resides in the UK builds on their knowledge of power and government. By exploring these concepts now, pupils can critically evaluate how power is allocated and exercised and how they can bring their voice to power, preparing them for informed participation in civic life.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils should understand the basic difference between local and national government.
Pupils should know that some powers are transferred to Scotland, Wales, and Northern Ireland.
Pupils should recognise the roles and structures of different levels of government.
Pupils should have a basic understanding of UK elections and voting processes.""" ;
  curric:id "3475"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.388471Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-politics-parliament-and-government .

oakcurric:unit-3473
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Why do we need the right to protest in a democracy?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils explore how rights have developed in the UK and how they are protected. They look at what changes in society have occurred due to protest."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Understanding the necessity of the right to protest in a democracy builds on pupils' knowledge of rights, justice and the law and their knowledge of active citizenship. This unit explores the role of protest in influencing change and protecting freedoms. It challenges pupils to critically consider what methods are acceptable to create change, supporting them to develop as informed and responsible citizens.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils understand the concept of legal rights and how they are protected through UK law.
Pupils know how citizens can participate in democracy, including through direct action and campaigning.
Pupils can identify how individuals and groups influence change within democratic systems.""" ;
  curric:id "3473"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.389493Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-rights-justice-and-the-law .

oakcurric:unit-3443
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How do democratic systems work around the world?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils explore how key democratic structures such as the justice system, the media and government operate across the globe and consider the impact this has on human rights and citizens ability to take action."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Learning how democratic systems work around the world builds on their knowledge of government and democracy within the UK. This unit provides a comparative perspective on different democratic practices and institutions. By exploring these concepts now, pupils can appreciate the diversity of democratic systems and critically consider the pros and cons of different democractic systems.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils understand how democracy works in the UK, including government, law, and media roles.
Pupils know what human rights are and how they are protected in law.
Pupils have learned about local and national governance and the importance of active participation.""" ;
  curric:id "3443"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.393060Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-uk-and-the-wider-world .

oakcurric:unit-3693
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How can we prepare well for financial decision making?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Using the example of housing, pupils explore a range of different financial decisions, products and services. They consider how they can prepare to become financially independent and what advice is available to them."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils existing knowledge of personal and public spending and their understanding of debt, credit loans, savings investment and risk. Using the example of housing, students critically consider how personal and public spending and economic decisions can impact housing nationally.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """What credit and loans are
What local authorities and national government fund
Financial challenges local and national government have
What taxes are and why we pay them
How citizens can support a healthy economy
What debt is""" ;
  curric:id "3693"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.396656Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-finance-and-the-economy .

oakcurric:unit-3457
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Should the UK be called a democracy?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils consider what makes a democracy, they explore key features of democracy in the UK and consider how those in power are held to account."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on pupils prior learning about what a democracy is. Pupils take a more in-depth look at how democracy works in the UK by exploring what parliament is, how we can hold those in power to account and the role of the press and media and select committees within democracy. The unit encourages critical thinking about governance, representation and citizens rights.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils should understand what democracy means and the key features that define it.
Pupils should recognise the structure and role of the UK Parliament.
Pupils should have a general awareness of the media’s role in society and the importance of free press.
Pupils should be familiar with the concept of devolution and its impact on governance.
Pupils should understand basic democratic participation methods and how citizens can get involved.""" ;
  curric:id "3457"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.446596Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-politics-parliament-and-government .

oakcurric:unit-3465
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "What are the strengths and weaknesses of the UK democratic system?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils develop their knowledge of democracy and the different types of democracy considering the strengths and weaknesses of the UK system."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils learn about the strengths and weaknesses of the UK democratic system and build on their previous knowledge of basic political concepts and structures. This unit deepens their understanding of democracy, encouraging critical thinking about different types of governance and how democracy can be strengthened.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know the difference between local, regional, and national government.
Pupils know how local councils work and who represents people in their area.
Pupils know there is a difference between government and Parliament.
Pupils know that we elect people to represent us.""" ;
  curric:id "3465"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.463441Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-politics-parliament-and-government .

oakcurric:unit-3454
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How does the international community respond to global humanitarian problems?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils consider what role the UK should have in tackling international conflict and global humanitarian problems, exploring different methods for conflict resolution."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Understanding the international community's response to global humanitarian problems builds on pupils' knowledge of UK and the wider world. This unit is timely as it examines mechanisms and strategies for addressing crises. By learning these concepts now, pupils can appreciate the role of international cooperation in solving global challenges, fostering a sense of global citizenship.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils understand how the UK engages with international organisations such as the UN, NATO and the Commonwealth.
Pupils can explain how citizens and governments contribute to solving societal problems, including through active citizenship and advocacy.
Pupils know how global issues can be addressed through cooperation and the role the UK plays in international responses.""" ;
  curric:id "3454"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.463942Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-uk-and-the-wider-world .

oakcurric:unit-3451
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How is social media changing our view of democracy?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils consider the impact that new forms of media are having on democracy using case studies from the UK and India."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Understanding how social media is changing our view of democracy builds on pupils' knowledge of governance and media influence. This unit is timely as it explores the impact of social media on political engagement, information dissemination, and public opinion. By learning these concepts now, pupils can critically assess digital media's role in democracy, making this education crucial for developing informed and discerning citizens.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know the media’s role in democracy and how it shapes public opinion.
Pupils understand digital media as a source of information and influence.
Pupils have explored different means of political engagement.""" ;
  curric:id "3451"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.674881Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-role-of-media-and-digital-democracy .

oakcurric:unit-3453
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How can politicians involve citizens in direct decision making?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Through a series of case studies from across the globe pupils explore different methods of direct democracy and consider how UK citizens can play a part in shaping national policy."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Understanding how politicians can involve citizens in direct decision-making builds on pupils knowledge of politics, parliament and government and their active citizenship skills. This unit is timely as it highlights mechanisms like referendums and consultations, exploring different methods for citizens to make their voices heard.  By learning these concepts now, pupils can advocate for and participate in direct democratic processes now and in the future.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know how the UK political system, parliament, and government work.
Pupils have explored the role of citizens in democracy and how they can participate.
Pupils understand different ways citizens can influence decisions and the importance of active engagement.""" ;
  curric:id "3453"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.689051Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-politics-parliament-and-government .

oakcurric:unit-3445
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "What can we do to reduce crime?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils explore how crime impacts the UK and consider the purpose of sentencing and whether current sentencing approaches in the UK are effective."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Understanding what can be done to reduce crime builds on their knowledge of rights, justice and the law. This unit explores strategies for crime prevention and rehabilitation. By learning these concepts now, pupils can contribute to creating safer communities through informed actions and advocacy.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know why laws exist.
Pupils understand the role of the justice system.
Pupils have have explored rights and responsibilities related to the justice system.""" ;
  curric:id "3445"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.699341Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-rights-justice-and-the-law .

oakcurric:unit-3463
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How does the media hold those in power to account?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils consider what role the media plays in democracy and how the media is used to hold those in power to account. They consider what responsible journalism is and the impact of misinformation."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Building on their key stage three learning about how the media impacts them this unit explores the important role the media plays within democracy. Through exploring concepts such as responsible journalism, censorship and misinformation pupils critically consider the importance of a free press to society.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils can explain why it is important to check if information is true and reliable.
Pupils know that the media plays a role in shaping society and public opinion.
Pupils recognise that media can have bias and affect how information is presented.""" ;
  curric:id "3463"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.699845Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-role-of-media-and-digital-democracy .

oakcurric:unit-3692
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How do we look after an ageing population?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils explore what role financial systems play in our communities, they consider what personal responsibility they have for financial planning and what role government plays in this, focussing on the impact our ageing population has on financial planning."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """In this unit pupils take their existing knowledge on personal and public finances and consider how our financial systems are responding to the changing population and the impact this is having. The unit builds on knowledge of both personal and government spending and encourages students to think critically about spending responsibilities across society.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Types of saving and investments
Different types of taxes collected by the government
How government spends taxes
How the UK government prevents and manages risk""" ;
  curric:id "3692"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.700823Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-finance-and-the-economy .

oakcurric:unit-3450
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How powerful is the media?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils explore the power and influence of the media both locally and nationally and consider how citizens can effectively navigate the information they are presented with."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Understanding how powerful the media is builds on pupils knowledge of the media and its role within a democractic society. This unit is timely as it examines the media's role in shaping perceptions, influencing policy, and holding power to account. By learning these concepts now, pupils can critically evaluate media content and its impact on society, preparing them to be media literate and informed citizens.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils understand the media’s role and responsibilities in society.
Pupils know how media can influence opinions and the importance of truth.
Pupils have considered how media shapes views locally and nationally.""" ;
  curric:id "3450"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.701339Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-role-of-media-and-digital-democracy .

oakcurric:unit-3467
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How does the economy work?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils learn what the economy is, what taxes are and consider local and central government spending and risk management."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on prior learning around personal finance and managing money through looking at basic economic concepts and principles. Pupils examines how the UK Government manages its finances and the impact on citizens and public services. By the end, pupils will understand the balance between economic decisions, taxation, and public service provision in the UK.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils can manage basic money skills like budgeting and saving.
Pupils understand the importance of managing money for future independence.
Pupils recognise that government financial decisions affect communities and services.""" ;
  curric:id "3467"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.702877Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-finance-and-the-economy .

oakcurric:unit-3459
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "What has the UK economy got to do with me?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit develops pupils' knowledge and understanding of the UK economy and helps them appreciate its relevance to them."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Understanding what the UK economy has to do with them builds on pupils existing knowledge of personal finance and basic economic concepts. The unit helps pupils connect macroeconomic concepts to their personal experiences, such as income, credit, debt and taxation. By learning these concepts now, pupils can better understand how economic policies and trends affect their future decisions and prospects.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils understand basic personal finance concepts like income, saving, and spending
Pupils know about credit, debt, and how they affect personal finances.
Pupils recognise the role of taxes and why people pay them.
Pupils can connect economic policies to their own lives and future decisions.""" ;
  curric:id "3459"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.712506Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-finance-and-the-economy .

oakcurric:unit-3460
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Does our legal system protect citizens' rights?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit builds pupils knowledge and understanding of the law and the legal system including: criminal and civil justice; the judicial process and role of citizens in justice; legal rights, sanctions; and how well prison works."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Understanding how the legal system protects citizens' rights builds on their knowledge of the key concepts of law and rights. This unit takes these concepts and looks at how they relate to each other.  By learning to consider these concepts synoptically now, pupils can better understand their rights and the legal protections available to them.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know why laws exist and the role of the justice system.
Pupils know there are different types of law i.e. criminal and civil.
Pupil have explored the roles of different legal professionals within the justice system.
Pupils understand what rights are and how they are protected in law.""" ;
  curric:id "3460"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.719028Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-rights-justice-and-the-law .

oakcurric:unit-3449
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How can the local economy support sustainability?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Using the example of sustainability, students consider the local economy and its impact on citizens and their local communities."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Exploring how the local economy can support sustainability builds on pupils' knowledge of finance and the economy. This unit is timely as it highlights sustainable practices and their importance for future generations. By learning these concepts now, pupils can advocate for and engage in sustainable economic activities.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils understand the role of taxation and government in supporting communities and public services.
Pupils know how citizens can contribute to and shape their local communities through active citizenship.
Pupils can explain the importance of economic decisions in addressing wider issues like sustainability and community wellbeing.""" ;
  curric:id "3449"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.723116Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-finance-and-the-economy .

oakcurric:unit-3461
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "What are the different ways we can become involved in politics?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils build knowledge and understanding of political systems, government, voting and elections. Pupils consider the vast range of political roles, exploring the impact that these roles can have across local communities and wider society and how they can get involved in politics."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Building on their growing knowledge of democracy, this unit further develops students understanding of political systems and civic engagement. The unit provides insight into how the UK political system and political systems around the world operate and examines the skills needed for a variety of roles within politics. This knowledge helps them to recognise the distinct roles and responsibilities within politics, fostering informed and active citizenship.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils understand the key features of a democratic system and the role of elected representatives in the UK.
Pupils know how elections work and how citizens can participate in democratic processes.
Pupils have examined how the media holds those in power to account and the importance of a free press.
Pupils have started to consider their own role in society and how they can take part in political and community action.""" ;
  curric:id "3461"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.734440Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-politics-parliament-and-government .

